	<p>Nice illustrations ang great article! But it isnt always necessary to use explicit positioning and z-index to stack elements on top of each other.</p>

	<p>1) Every nested element is one level higher then its parent. This is why &#8220;sliding door&#8221; technique can work.</p>

	<p>2) Every floatad element is higher then not floated (and not positioned) elements. &#8220;Faux columns&#8221; is based on this fact.</p>

	<p>3) In some cases we can use negativ margins &#8220;to pull back&#8221; the next element.</p>
</div>
